## Major Risks and Early Control Measures

| Risk | Control |
|---|---|
| Poor issuer and instrument mapping | Treat canonicalization as a first-class service and persist rejection reasons. |
| Hidden data quality issues in prices or maturities | Add explicit quality rules and diagnostics before calibration. |
| Inconsistent mathematics between research and production | Enforce a single shared quantitative core package. |
| Assignment logic duplicated across consumers | Publish one authoritative curve assignment table. |
| Lack of audit trail for published outputs | Persist run, config, code, and publication metadata with every output. |
| Over-engineering deployment too early | Prioritize quantitative correctness and stable schemas before platform complexity. |

## Phase 2 Extension: CDS

The phase 1 architecture is intentionally structured so CDS can be introduced without replacing the platform:

- ingestion adds CDS quote sources
- canonicalization adds RED code and maturity normalization
- quant core adds ISDA-style RPV01 and CDS pricing support
- calibration objective adds joint bond plus CDS fitting
- signal engine adds bond-CDS basis analytics

This should be a modular extension to existing services rather than a redesign.

## Conclusion

An industrial-scale bond relative value platform should be built as a disciplined analytics production system, not as a loose collection of notebooks, research scripts, or point tools. The immediate priorities are stable data contracts, clean quantitative boundaries, controlled calibration workflows, and full auditability of published outputs. If the platform is built in the prescribed order, the resulting system will support large-scale coverage, reproducible daily production, robust downstream delivery, and a clean upgrade path into CDS-enhanced calibration.
